^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There are very few hands where 5 of a minor plays better than 3N. And I don't tend to worry too much about voids playing 3N. In this case, since my void is in spades, it is unlikely partner has more than 4 spades, so you are very likely to get a spade lead, so that is a bit of a worry. So, here it is more possible than usual that 5D is a better contract than 3N. However, my years of experience tell me 3N is usually best. So, with 10 HCP and a very nice diamond suit, I bid 3N and hope that it makes. We often will be able to take 9 tricks off the top, and even if we can't , it is possible we have spades double stopped.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Your other choice is to jump to 5D. I would not fault someone for doing that, but it also would not surprise me if that contract went down. It is also possible that you can make six diamonds if partner has the right cards, but without a sophisticated bidding system that allows you to explore for a minor suit slam over a 1N opener, it would be difficult to bid.
|
