at|^-{Odd/Even Discard}
^-|qx|O1,return|CS||CP||fp|2|at|^C@2^Y@3The first time you discard (you don't follow suit), Odd/Even works as follows. If you discard an odd card in a suit, that is encouraging attitude. If you discard an even card, that is discouraging attitude. It only applies to your first discard. After that, standard signaling is in effect. A few, but not many, people play that an even card is suit preference (e.g. a low even is suit preference for the lower of the remaining suits, a high even is suit preference for the higher of the remaining suits--like Lavinthal discards), but I recommend against that. In general, I am not a fan of suit preference, other than the one special case where you lead back a suit that you know partner is trumping.	|
